    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-30T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-30T05:00:00-05:00" n="953"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d953">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1314: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="10" xml:id="d953fn10">Quoted to the Minister in China in Department’s
                        telegram No. 258, July 31, 6 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-30T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 30, 1931—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 30—6:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>276. Department’s telegram 238, July 27, 4 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d953fn11">Not
                        printed.</note> Foreign Office states orally British Government’s policy is
                    that no arms or munitions of war including military aeroplanes can leave Great
                    Britain without Board of Trade export license given only after consulting with
                    Foreign Office. In the case of China, Foreign Office concurrence is only given
                    to shipments destined for and with the known sanction of the Nanking Government.
                    As regards Hong Kong local Government was requested to conform to British
                    Government’s policy as above stated. The Hong Kong Government is doing so.
                    Foreign Office states <pb facs="1133" n="1023" xml:id="pg_1023"/> further that
                    commercial aeroplanes can be exported to China or anywhere without reference to
                    Board of Trade or Foreign Office, no export license being required.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
